    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Anne Stevenson's otherwise responsible review of ''Robert Graves and the White Goddess,'' by Richard Perceval Graves (Nov. 10), ignores what is most important about Robert Graves.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Anne Stevenson's otherwise responsible review of ''Robert Graves and the White Goddess,'' by Richard Perceval Graves (Nov. 10), ignores what is most important about Robert Graves.</p>
        <p>When the reviewer wonders what of Graves will survive, she cites only prose works, as if the poetry were of lesser importance. So, too, she calls ''She Tells Her Love While Half Asleep'' Graves's ''most famous love poem,'' as though this charming seven-liner were some sort of isolated peak. In fact, it is at the very least equaled in fineness and, I would assume, fame by, for example, ''Lost Love,'' ''Pure Death,'' ''The Thieves,'' ''Counting the Beats'' and ''A Lost Jewel.'' The greatness of Graves as a love poet rests in</p>
        <p>a body of poems.</p>
        <p>John Simon  New York</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
